english:
  title: Reply to the Eastern Xia Kingdom
  author: Yu Seung-dan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The King of Goryeo humbly submits this reply to Your Majesty, the King of Eastern Xia.

    Having received your esteemed letter, I note your words regarding the sacred decree of Emperor Genghis Khan, that the King of Eastern Xia shall prepare to receive an imperial audience. Goryeo, standing as we do upon the foundation of our previous treaty of friendship where both realms were deemed equal in station, shall likewise prepare to send our delegation in due course. Yet I must address your inquiry as to whether we shall indeed come.

    Consider that our small kingdom lies at the edge of the sea, remote and obstructed by distant mountains and rivers. Since ancient times we have served great powers, yet never has our sovereign journeyed in person to render the rites of court audience. Now that Emperor Genghis Khan has cast wide the illuminating threads of his rule, bringing all lands beneath his dominion so that none resist where sun and moon shine, my heart trembles with gratitude for the compassion extended to our humble state. Like a duck upon the water, I have long yearned to fly forth with felicitations, yet the path stretches far and natural barriers divide us. In ages past, when envoys traveled between our lands, their journeys proved perilous; how much more difficult would it be if I myself should abandon my post? Though our realm is small, the duties of state bind us—not a single day can pass without our sovereign at his station. Should I recklessly leave my throne and traverse ten thousand li, only to encounter unforeseen calamity, I fear the great virtue of the Emperor might be tarnished by such consequence. For this reason, though my gaze turns ever upward in reverence, my heart can only tremble with cautious concern.

    As the ancients wrote, "To cherish the virtuous and befriend the neighboring states is the treasure of a kingdom." Our realm is fortunate to share borders with your noble nation, and though our peoples gaze upon each other from afar with goodwill, the spirit of good neighborliness binds us in mutual understanding. Not the slightest discord exists between us. I beseech you to reflect deeply upon this.

    As the year wanes and the new spring approaches, I humbly pray for your continued wellbeing. This reply is respectfully submitted.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: '成吉思 (Genghis Khan): This refers to Temüjin, founder of the Mongol Empire, indicating the historical context of Mongol supremacy in East Asia during the 13th century.'
  - key: ''
    value: '朝覲 (court audience): The formal ritual of vassal states presenting themselves before their sovereign or overlord.'
  - key: ''
    value: '鷰賀 (felicitations/congratulations): Here rendered poetically—the reference to swallows bringing congratulations evokes the imagery of humble messengers bearing good tidings.'
  - key: ''
    value: '善隣 (good neighborliness): A Confucian diplomatic principle emphasizing mutual respect and peaceful relations between neighboring states.'
